Finding the cheater, An analysis of chess statistics¶

By, Alexander Ramirez

Background info¶

On september 4th, The world of chess exploded after American Grandmaster, Hans Niemann defeated Magnus Carlsen. Normally you would not think much of this statment, given that we are just talking about a game with three outcomes, winning, losing and ending in a draw. Allegations of cheating arose after the current world champion Carlsen withdrew from a tournement after the loss. And only two weeks later he reisgned after the third move of the against Niemann. Only to directly accuse him of cheating afterwards.

Cheating has become more of an issue in chess in the past decade. In recent years we have seen the rise of Chess engines that are virtually impossible to beat, even the best players in the world Carlsen is projected to only win in 1 out of 180 games. These engines are able to see far further in the future then what is possible for humans, and make moves that dont make sense that only come into play many turns later, moves that human are unable to make due to out own limitations. Though how he could of cheated in person is another discussion entirely.

The Data¶

Both of these datasets contains close to 20,000 games from the lichess dataset. Lichess uses a public API which allows me to direclty acess more data as needed using the Berserk python client to interface the API. The only issue is that with large requests it can take really long to complete. If interested, refer to the Lichess API or Berserk documentations.

Understanding chess_1¶

This dataset is composed of entirely rated games. Rated games is when both players play with their ratings at risk, this is important since typically you would expect players to take these games more seriously.

The columns

  • Game ID:
    • This is the unique identier for every game that lichess has saved. This is used to acess game data not in the database.
  • black/white rating
    • The rating of both players moving first
    • White always moves first
    • Range approx. (100, 3000)
  • Opening ECO
    • Code system for classifing openers, These are labeled a-e and 00-99. (most common openers)
  • Centi-pawn Loss
    • The data listed will be aCPL or average centipawn loss, This is evaluation score that the chess engine provides after each turn that us averaged over the entire game. It evaluates your move against its own optimal move on the board
    • The range goes from [0,100)
    • Given that it is being compared to the optimal move, a chess engine's centipawn loss should be extremely close to 0. But a master player's loss is generally close to 30.
    • Low loss does not imply cheating, plently of good players had games with extremely low aCPLs
  • Inaccuracies
    • Not a good move, but it is not game losing. You can regain your position.
  • Mistakes
    • A poor move, gives your opponent the upper hand or somthing like a missed win
  • Blunders
    • A terrible move, you can single handidly lose the game becasue of this move. Can also be somthing like missing mate.

Helper function to add cols from the Lichess API¶

In [77]:
# Never use this on the entire dataset I havent tried but i can assume that 
# first it will take too long and use up too many resourses, but it might also
# might just block that many requests. Only use on small subsets of the 
# dataframe. For example when binning by opener or by elo. 
def add_col(df, target_col):
  df_cpy = df.copy()
  val_arr = df['Game ID'].apply(lambda x: client.games.export(x)[target_col])
  df_cpy.insert(2, target_col, val_arr, True)
  return df_cpy

Detecting the cheater¶

In this section, I hope to find the components with the highest realtionship with winning or losing. By finding those dimensions I will be able to see trends of what is normal and what is an outlier. These outliers may prove useful in detecting cheaters given how, the matches they play will most likely produce results that are not to be expected. This is because, chess is a game of skill not of luck. If you lose you made a mistake that costed you, the better player should generally win.

Organsing the data by elo¶

As stated above chess is a game of skill, so how it is played changes dramatically by the elo. Extremely simplified catagories of ratings:

  1. Masters: 2000+
  2. Really good players: 1500 - 2000
  3. Good players: 1000 - 1500
  4. Novices: Below 1000

For the sake of this i will be ignoring the novices since the games tend to be more unpredictables. This should make the data much more comprehensible with less randomness, making the outliers much more visable.

Centipawn loss in relation to diffrence in rating¶

Centipawn loss is the measument of accuracy of the entire game, of how close were the moves the player made were to the engines best move. A very high score can be interpreted as every turn the player made some of the worst moves possible. While a very low score means its playing similar to how the engine would have played.

In this case where we are measuring loss in relation to rating diffrences, I expect the player with the lower score to have a higher loss given how when playing agaisnt a better player the worse player should be making more mistakes and play poorly in comparision.

Interestingly by looking at the plots we can see a pattern that the vast majority of games are within a 400 player rating diffrence. Within this range we can see the player with less elo generally ends the game with around 50-75 aCPL. But as the diffrence in elo increases, aCPL decreases. This does not follow normal intuition since you would expect as the player skill difference increases so would the the average amount of bad moves, but that is not what is shown. This can only be really explained in two ways, either the player is much better than what their elo claims them to be so they are playing against better people to quickly gain elo. Or they are using some sort of unauthorized assitance. This fact is much more evident in the plot where we were tracking the black players aCPL, there was a game with approximatly a 1400 elo gap but the weaker player had a aCPL of around 20 which is extremely good. To put the score in perspective Grandmasters like Carlsen rarely get less than 10 aCPL against players their own skill level. A performace like that can not be passed up as pure luck.

This plot reinforces the claims made in the the average centipawn loss visualiztion. The data is conterintuive, as the gap in skill increases the chances of making any one of the three mistakes decreases instead of increasing. These plots show why the centipawn loss were so low in the games with huge gaps. But it does not provide an explanation to why it occurs. Players in the 2000+ range are much less likely to make any of the mistakes especially blunders, so given that they comprise almost all the markers beyond the 1000 elo diferece means players likely near 1000 rating are playing well if not better than players who are rated over 2000. The 2000 rated players should not be giving away free pieces, they should be doing discover checks or other tactics a lower leveled player would not be able to forsee or react to.

What dimensions matter¶

  1. Opening side: There is a slight benefit for the player starting white but it is not significant. There is also no indicator on who may or may not be cheating. But it does show no matter what side the player is on the the effect of the other features will be the same.
  2. Opening ECO: No specific benefits of choosing one opener over the other, though some had higher win rates. But it cannot be used in identifying cheaters using chess engines since openers are consitent moves and only use up around three turns. Afterwards is when the engine becomes useful since it is able to account for the entire board rather than a single pawn at e4.
  3. aCPL: First useful metric, by itself it does not have much value but combigned with player ratings it can show when a player is playing very well with a large skill gap. But also if a player has less than 5 aCPL there is a very high probability that they are cheating regardless of elo. This is occurs because engines make moves often called "bot moves" which they interpret as the best move but it's a human would never normally make. An example would be sacrificing a queen for a tactic that would come into play 5 turns in the future.
  4. diffrence in elo: This will be the core metric, since it puts the game into perspective. aCPL alone is very consisitent no matter the elo. But as the diffrence in elo changes the other stats should trend negatively, unless they are much better than their elo or they are cheating.
  5. number of mistakes: similar to aCPL, but better players will make less mistakes then lower rated players. As the elo gap increases not only does the data become more scarse the few games that show up it seems like the number of mistakes made by the lower rated player also decreases. this is beacasue of the matchmaking system.
  6. winning: Just like aCPL and # mistakes, this is highly dependent on the elo diffrence. Best represented by the 3D scatter we saw that most games were played within a certain range of elo with similar liklihood of winning and losing but there were a few of outliers that created suspicous markers.

Matchmaking system¶

The lichess matchmaking system will attempt to match players of a 300 elo diffrence and have not played against each other in a session, if such a match is not found it will broaden the results. The issue is that when you perform really well it will attempt to lessen the diffrence and match you against better players, but this does not happen frequently which shows how good the rating system. And as an unintended benefit it creates very obvious outliers, wheter thay are cheating or they are making a new account of somthing along those lines cannot be decided without further analysis.

Predicting the Cheater¶

After the data analysis I found the the most significant features for finding outliers are: player rating, winner, and aCPL. With these features i beleive that i can make a high dimensional classifiaction algorithm to classify cheaters from normal players. Naturally this will be a nonsupervised since none of the datasets contain a feature for this, but my workaround is searcing for the player in the API and seeing if they were banned or not.

K-Means clustering¶

Params

  1. number of clusters
  2. Method for initialization:
    1. k-means++ : selects initial cluster centroids using sampling based on an empirical probability distribution of the points contribution to the overall inertia.
    2. random: choose n_clusters observations (rows) at random from data for the initial centroids.
  3. random_state: Determines random number generation for centroid initialization.

For now lets try DBSCAN. In this situation DBSCAN may be very powerful due to how it performs clustering.

A very top level explanation¶

The algoritm has starting points from those points it checks all the surrounding points, if those points meet a certain threshold in quantanty and distance, it calls itself a core node. These nodes are what makes up the cluster, once all of the core nodes are found we are left with the non-core points. These points can be added to the cluster if they meet the distance requrment but they cannot be used for extending the cluster. Everything else is left unclustered as an outlier.

This seems like it would work perfectly in my use case since it will hopefully be able to identify the two large clusters while excluding the outliers which im hoping are the cheaters.

DBSCAN¶

Parameter Estimation¶

The general rule of thumb for choosing the min_samples is to multiply the dimensionality of the input by 2. It should also noted there are some other cases where you want to increase the min_samples which are: large datasets and noisy data. My data does not satisfy either of those so im going to stick to min_samples = 2*dim.

Finding the min distance(eps)¶

Treat the distance as the radius around the point, we want to see if any points are within that radius. I will be finding the average distance between points using the min_samples nearest neighbors.

In [97]:

distances = np.sort(distances, axis=0)

The plot tells the 8NN distance in respect to sample size, with the y-axis is the 8-NN distance and the x-axis is the number of samples. so we want to find the distance where we can get good clustering but not overfit. From this we can approximate the knee of the plot is around .3, but since i want only around 2 clusters i want the distance to be slightly larger. Since any higher the clusters will be too large and any lower it will result in too many clusters.

In [107]:
def get_banned(df):
  cheaters = []
  for idx, row in df.iterrows():
    if ((client.users.get_by_id(row['white_id']))[0].get('disabled') == True) :
        cheaters.append(row['white_id'])
    if ((client.users.get_by_id(row['black_id']))[0].get('disabled') == True) :
        cheaters.append(row['white_id'])
  return cheaters

Here we can see that the desnisty based clustering method was much more successfull. Not only were there significantly less cheater classifications the clusters are actually understandable. If we refer back to the plot we can see 2 main clusters that we can charactorize as valid white win and valid black win, along with some small subclusters along the border of the large clusters. The only points not in the clusters are the outliers, exactly what i was looking for. Though this is where some issues arise, the first issue is on the low diff outliers, these occur in the corners where either both player's scores are extremely high or extremely low. Because of the extremes there are not many points around them making them an outlier, because of this these valid games are being treated as cheaters. The other issue is that there are still too many cheater classifications, in the last models it made 264 cheater classifications when in that one list there were only 67 classificaitons. So only 1/4 of its classifications were correct. So this model had allot of false positives with an unknown number of false negatives. To fix the issue of false positives we would either increase the distance between neighbors and or decrease the number of reqired neighbors, but doing either of those puts it at risk of overfit on the dataset.

Comments on cheating¶

First, just because one of the players that have not been banned does not imply that they did not cheat in that specific game. Im not sure for lichess but i know many algorithms need multiple instances of games to make an actual verdict. But on the other end of the stick some of the players that have been banned might have tirggered somthing in their system without ever cheating. Finally this model will not care whatsoever if the elo are close together. The thing is as people keep on cheating they will play against better players then it would raise a flag but before that the model would see them as a valid player

Conclusion¶

Unfortunately, the model is not sufficent in detecting cheaters. There is simply not enough dimensonality to the dataset. Though it was possible to add more dimensions it was to too time and resourse intensive to be reasonable. But compared to the inital algorithm the densisty based clustering performed infinitly better. But though it did not successfully locate cheaters it did find a correlation betweern the diffrence in rating and outcome. In genreral with more time and data it is possible to create a much more accurate model by taking in more dimenesionality such as wait time between turns or a function able to calculate accuracy given some arbitary turn of the board. But as project I succesfully was able to show the data life-cycle in a data science project.
